    "prompt": "<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Two figures titled Collision 1 and Collision 2 show top views of a bar rotating counterclockwise about a pivot at one end, labelled point P, on a horizontal surface before striking a disk. Collision 1 shows that the bar stops rotating at the point it strikes the disk while the disk moves to the right. Collision 2 shows that the bar continues rotating in the same direction after it strikes the disk while the disk moves to the right.\" src=\"/images/a0870b994a4914bff3d3dfaad2a56dc2.svg\"></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">In the two collisions depicted in the figures, a bar is rotating about a pivot at one end, labeled Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math></span></span>, on top of a horizontal surface before striking a disk that is initially at rest. The two collisions use the same bar but different disks, where the two disks are the same mass and size but are made of different materials. After each collision, the disk moves to the right at a constant velocity. After Collision <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>, the bar stops rotating. After Collision <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, the bar is still rotating in the same direction, and the disk is moving more slowly than after Collision <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. There is negligible friction between the bar and the pivot, between the bar and the surface, and between each disk and the surface. Which of the following correctly compares the magnitudes <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"J sub 1\"><math alttext=\"J sub 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>J</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"J sub 2\"><math alttext=\"J sub 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>J</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></span></span> of the angular impulse delivered to each disk during the respective collisions, and provides evidence that supports the claim?</p>\n",
